title: For Sale:  Egyptian Maadi ak 7.62x39 rifle
postcontent:
I am selling my baby, it took me a couple years to build/set up this rifle the way it is now. This is NOT a century or any other mass produced rifle. The fit and finish is excellent quality on this rifle. It is of course 922r complient. 

-Built from a Maadi (egyptian AKM) parts kit 
 -Barrel assembly was assembled/headspaced by Childers guns. I sent it down to them because of their reputation for quality work. Headspace was double checked and it was perfect.
 -Built on a new Nodak Spud reciever, the best quality reciever you can build on. These magazines fit very snugly in the reciever, no mag wobble
 -I didn't like the factory sheperds hook retainer for the trigger assembly parts so I replaced with a plate. Makes those parts much easier to replace/install
 -Romanian hammer forged chrome lined barrel, very good quality barrels that will last forever (I'm not sure that you can even get them anymore now that the Cuger factory in Romania is no longer exporting to the US) The chrome lining is also much more resistand to corrosive ammo than non-lined barrels
 -Very nice quality wood that was worked over, has a nice color/grain to it
 -Bolt carrier assembly/trigger parts polished to a chrome like finish, looks very nice and is functional. The polished surfaces make the bolt assembly much smoother operating and makes it very easy to clean.
 -Bakelite handgrip is in new conditon and also has very nice color
 -Krebs custom rear sight (very functional, very nice upgrade to the standard rear leaf)
 -Sling
 -slant brake for that classic cold war look
 -Retracting front bipod (has that rough functional ak look to it)
 -bayonette included
 -cleaning rod there
 -I only have the one magazine pictured but will include a second as well (couldn't find it this morning)
 -The rifle was Cerakoted by Dakota Custom Rifle
 -Has russian akm cleaning kit hidden in the buttstock 
 -I will also include a slide fire stock, its kind of a novelty but cool way to simulate FA fire. 

Some history, the Egyptian AK's were copys of the Russian AKM. During the cold war the Russians packed up an entire factory in russia and sent it to Egypt. they also send factory workers down there to train them how to build the ak's. So this AKM parts kit was built off the exact same machines that the russian ones were. 

In building the rifle and the slide fire stock I have arpox $1700.00 into the setup. I am VERY firm on my $1100.00 price. The only way I will negotiate is if you don't want the slide fire stock i can keep that and sell that seperately. Quality products cost money. 

I'm sure there is stuff I'm forgetting, as I find reciepts/remember stuff I will update.

title: For Sale:  Kel-tec RFB 308 Rifle New In Box
location: Kings Mtn., North Carolina, United States
postcontent: Kel-Tec RFB18 RFB SA 308 Winchester 18" Blk Syn  RFB stands for Rifle Forward-ejecting Bullpup. Forward-ejecting allows theRFB to be the first truly ambidextrous 7.62 NATO Bullpup. The patented,dual-extractor system maintains control of the case from the moment itleaves the magazine and upon firing, pulls the fired case from the chamberand lifts them to push them into an ejection chute above the barrel, wherethey exit. The RFB is a short-stroke gas piston operated semi-automaticrifle in 7.62 mm NATO caliber. All controls are fully ambidextrous; thereciprocating operating handle can be switched to either side. The safetydisconnects the trigger and blocks the hammer action. The Bullpupconfiguration and tilting-block mechanism allow the 18" model to be only26.1" long, or as much as 14" shorter in overall length than itscompetitors with equal barrel lengths. The stock and mechanismcross-section is similar to a conventional rifle, in stark contrast toexisting Bullpup rifles. The RFB is also the safest Bullpup developedbecause the breech is separated from the shooter's face by two layers of1.6 mm steel. In the highly unlikely event of a case rupture, gas expansionis directed downwards through the magazine well to protect the shootershead and face. postcontent:
Brand new in boxes of 100

$22/box of 100

Hornady XTP bullets were designed for hunting, self-defense, and law enforcement. One of the great things about the XTP bullet is reliable performance, it features controlled expansion where six serrations divide the bullet into six symmetrical sections. These sections weaken the jacket to allow controlled expansion at low velocities and ensures fragmentation does not occur at high velocities. The XTP bullet is really known for its stopping power. They were designed from the beginning to expand reliably at a variety of handgun velocities and deliver deep, terminal penetration with every shot. Most handgun bullets are designed to perform at a single factory-specified velocity where the XTP bullet is designed to offer controlled expansion over a range of velocities. 

Each XTP Bullet has a swaged core and drawn copper jacket to ensure uniform expansion and in-flight stability. Adding a cannelure to this bullet keeps the core and the jacket locked together while also allowing the cartridge case to tightly crimp, adding security at high velocities. This is not loaded ammunition.

title: For Sale:  COLT 1911 MADE 1913
postcontent: As did every other combatant nation at the onset of the First World War, Britain suffered from arms shortages and began placing orders with American companies to help take up the slack. In 1912, the British started purchasing some 1911 pistols from Colt. With the outbreak of hostilities, it was decided to purchase additional pistols and by 1919 in excess of 17,000 had been delivered. Pistols in both .45 ACP and .455 Auto Mark I were obtained. The former were marked with a "C" serial number prefix while the latter had a "W" prefix. This 1911 serial # C-4649 caliber 45 acp was made is 1913 and a letter from the Colt archives states it was one of 20 pistols shipped to the London Armory Company on May 4, 1914. This was prior to the opening shots of the War which occurred on July 28, 1914. This pistol undoubtedly saw service in the hands of a British Officer during the Great War! The frame and slide have the British proofs. The over all finish is about 30% with the trigger, hammer, slide release and safety showing about 50% of the nitre blue finish. Barrel is marked HS on the lug and the letter P. Rifling is excellent! Grips are in good shape for a 101 year old War veteran. The magazine is a two tone correct punch and saw cut with lanyard loop. With the approaching anniversary of the start of the Great War July 28,1914 - November 11, 1918 this is your opportunity to own a piece of history. While it has not been researched yet it may be possible to discover which British Officer carried this pistol adding to the collectible and increasing the value! The Colt letter verifying the shipment information is included    C&R License accepted
